Sainsbury plans to conquer the perfume and cosmetics market in the UK
Sainsbury is going to install cosmetics and perfumery departments in the stores of Boots, Superdrag and Debenhams with consultants and cosmetologists, according to the model of luxury department stores.
The UK perfumery and cosmetics market is valued at 2.8 billion pounds and continues to expand, while in fashion and home goods sales are falling. To capture a significant share of this coveted market, spacious cosmetics and perfumery departments will be presented as an experiment in 11 stores across the country, and if successful next year, they should be expected in many other stores.
Supermarket owners are looking for something to fill the shelves, previously reserved for televisions, microwave ovens, household goods, and investment in the perfume and cosmetics market seems to be a good solution.
According to Sainsbury, it is planned to double the range of cosmetic products to 3 thousand items, including for the first time such brands as Revlon, Essie, Tweezerman and Dr. PawPaw will be offered.
The existing range from L'Oreal, Maybelline and Burt's Bees will be presented on a larger scale, in dedicated locations, by type of organization of goods in Booths stores.
In addition, the Butik-Cosmetics branded product line will be reorganized with the transition to vegan products to meet the demands of young buyers.
Two of Sainsbury's stores will feature Fragrance Shop's perfume stalls: the first one has already opened in Croydon in south London last week, and the second one is expected to open in Selly Oak, Birmingham, this year.
E-commerce and the tendency to buy a small amount of food for each day in small shops near the house led to the fact that supermarkets are forced to attract buyers in other ways.
Mike Coop, president of Sainsbury, says outlets will gradually turn into department stores, and his supermarket chain is fighting for buyers in a competitive battle with cheap stores like Aldi and Lidl, offering more services and non-food items.
Hundreds of supermarkets in Sainsbury have Argos outlets, and some now have Habitats stores since the chain acquired both brands two years ago. This has led to increased sales of food products and revenue from these acquisitions.
Previous attempts by the supermarket to give new life to its cosmetic and pharmacy departments have not been successful.
In the early 2000s, a joint venture was organized between Sainsbury and Booths, but later disagreements arose between the participants in the issue of dividing the income from the sales of pharmacy products in supermarkets.
The new strategy was developed after the sale of the pharmaceutical business of Sainsbury (a total of 281 stores) to Celesio, the owner of the Lloyds Farmasi network, for 125 million pounds three years earlier.
Lloyds is expected to support the implementation of the plan by adding a wide range of luxury skin care products La Roche-Posay and Vichy in four stores.
Paul Mills-Hicks, Sainsbury’s Chief Commercial Officer, said: “We have completely transformed the look and feel of our perfume and cosmetics departments to create a more welcoming environment for our customers.
We also invited specially trained consultants who will always be ready to help with advice.
Our range of brands for every taste, pleasant design and convenient location of shops will attract many visitors in search of cosmetics and perfumes. This will be a completely new concept of shopping.”
