John Edward: Knowledge of languages is essential for the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland continue the tradition of brilliant education, which was once again confirmed in 2018: outstanding exam results demonstrated individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other socially significant disciplines.
These schools are part of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), with more than 30,000 students across Scotland seeking to provide the highest level of services to students and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further higher education, their chosen careers, as well as the status of citizens of the world.
As part of the education sector, which is responsible for the development and implementation of an individual school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you are calling to his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, you turn to his heart.”
This is convincing evidence that we cannot rely only on the English language if we want to build relationships with citizens of other countries and be able to trust them.
According to the results of the last exams this year, we see that languages occupy a leading position in the league tables and have the highest score on the results of exams in independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of foreign language learners received a top grade of “A”.
Data from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students received an “A” in Mandarin (an adverb of Chinese), while 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners, and 63 percent of Spanish learners also received an “A.”
This proves that in independent schools in Scotland, foreign languages are undoubtedly considered vital for children and young people in the future.
Currently, language subjects are in the same demand as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and in other educational institutions.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that among the reasons employers had difficulty filling job vacancies, 17 per cent were due to a lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly becoming the key to a successful future career for young people.
Given that more promising jobs require language skills, these skills are needed in a globalized world.
No matter what profession the student chooses, if he learns a second language, in the future he will get a real advantage by mastering another additional skill that will be useful to him throughout his later life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows several foreign languages a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to support the conversation, and French was the only language with a double-digit percentage — it is spoken by 15 percent of respondents.
That’s why investing in language education is so important now.
Knowing multiple languages, especially those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
In schools in Scotland, there is a fairly wide range in terms of languages that are taught - each school has its own set of languages.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK in light of the country's future development through 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of your child, independent schools will always have a choice of several languages with teaching staff, whose members are specialists in these languages.
Scotland’s independent schools aim to create a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
At present, it cannot be denied that in the global business environment, languages are still vital for the future development of the country, so this must be reflected in education accordingly.
In fact, modern languages really need to be considered as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, providing diversity and benefits for Scotland's youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edwards, Director of the Council of Independent Schools of Scotland
