North Korea says it will not unilaterally disarm without trust
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions increase distrust of the United States and that his country will not give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally under any circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “substantial goodwill measures” last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site, and committing not to build up stockpiles of nuclear weapons or develop nuclear technology.
“However, we do not see a symmetrical reaction from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, we will not be able to unilaterally take the first steps toward disarmament.”
While Ri echoed North Korea’s already-sounding complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization that would reward North Korea for incremental steps, his statement seemed important in the sense that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization without control, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri cited a joint statement made by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to begin a move toward “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” and Trump promised North Korea security guarantees.
North Korea seeks to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington is also resisting calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that ‘denuclearisation must be carried out first,’ and raises the level of pressure through sanctions to enforce its goal and even objects to ‘an announcement of an end to the war,’” Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a utopian dream of people who don’t know us.
But the real problem is that the ongoing sanctions increase our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister focused on three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea, not the United States, had been a party to this denuclearization issue, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have ended up in such a dead end.”
However, the tone of Ri’s speech was sharply different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea’s missiles on the U.S. mainland was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “suicide missile.”
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said much remained to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not set a timeline for the process: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should encourage Pyongyang for the steps that have been taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The imposition of sanctions by the Security Council must continue actively and necessarily until we see complete, final and confirmed denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions on North Korea since 2006, seeking to cut off funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly summit and said after that meeting that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for the second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times so far this year, but his latest trip has failed.
In July, he left Pyongyang, saying progress had been made, but within hours of that visit, North Korea condemned him for “bandit demands.”
North Korea promised at a meeting held with Moon this month to dismantle the missile complex, as well as the nuclear complex, if the United States, for its part, takes “appropriate measures.”
Kim told him that the “appropriate measures” he was talking about were the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore, as well as actions aimed at normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students learn to relax in special courses
The new course, introduced this year at Harvard University, has helped all elementary students learn to sleep more and combat the chauvinist culture of continuous caffeine consumption in order to stay awake all night long.
One academic found that the most successful students in the world often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chaisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
After his discovery was made, he got excited about the idea of introducing such a course, having previously made a presentation on the impact of lack of sleep on learning processes.
“At the end of my report, a girl came up to me and said, ‘I’m sorry I only found out about this now that I’m almost finishing my studies.’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first offered to students this year, talks about how the habit of healthy sleep contributes to academic and sports performance, as well as how it improves the overall well-being of a person.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University Health Service, says the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were experiencing severe sleep deprivation during the school week.
The lesson lasts one hour, students perform a number of interactive tasks.
One section of the class offers a picture of a dormitory room, where students, by clicking on coffee cups, curtains, exercisers, and books, get information about how each of these activities and substances — coffee, light, which cause a lack of sleep — affect athletic performance, and how important it is to get enough sleep every day.
In another section, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The interactive campus map encourages course participants to reflect on their daily lives.
“We understand that these classes will not change the behavior of students at once.
But we believe they have a right to know, just like anyone else has a right to know, for example, how smoking affects their health,” added Professor Chaisler.
A false sense of pride that a person can “smelle all night” is still fairly common, he said, and modern technology, as well as increasing pressure on students, means sleep deprivation is becoming a problem.
According to him, a sufficient amount of good quality sleep is a “secret weapon” for a student to deal with stress, nervous exhaustion and anxiety, and even to combat excess weight, as lack of sleep puts the brain in starvation mode, causing him to constantly feel hungry.
Raymond Soe, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped develop the course by attending one of the classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to spread this information across campus.
He hopes the next step is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar curriculum before enrolling in a competitive institution.
Professor Chaisler recommends that students set an alarm clock warning that you need to go to bed and wake up, as well as remember the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lamps, which disrupts a person’s biorhythm and leads to problems with falling asleep.
