Almanac: Inventor of the Geiger Counter
And now the page of our almanac "Sunday Morning": September 30, 1882, 136 years ago on this day in Germany was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the creation of a device known as the Geiger counter.
Becoming one of the foundations of science, the Geiger counter also became one of the foundations of popular culture, and this was reflected in the 1950s film Coronado Bells, with cowboy-like Roy Rogers and Dale Evans — such seemingly unlike scientists — in the lead roles:
Man: "What kind of thing is that?"
Rogers: "This is a Geiger counter, used to detect radioactive minerals like uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can really hear the effects of atoms generated by the radioactivity in the minerals.”
Evans: "Here, you can hear it right now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945 just days before his 63rd birthday.
But his invention, named after its author, is still widely used.
