What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it done anything to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York City will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event featuring an impressive stellar lineup with an equally impressive mission to end poverty around the world.
For the seventh year as part of the Festival of World Citizens, tens of thousands of people flock to the large lawn of Central Park, but not only to enjoy performances by artists such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Sean Mendes, but also to talk about the real goal of the event: the eradication of extreme poverty by 2030.
The World Citizens Festival, which opened in 2012, is a follow-up to a global anti-poverty project led by an international group of human rights defenders hoping to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
To get a free event ticket (unless you’re willing to pay for a VIP ticket), you had to volunteer or send an email to a world leader, make a phone call, or take any other or other meaningful action to help raise awareness of your goal of ending poverty.
But how successful has the Festival of World Citizens been in 12 years in terms of achieving its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people by freely attending a concert really convincing fellow citizens to demand a call to action, or is it just another case of so-called “clickivism” where people believe they are making real changes by signing an online petition or sending messages on Twitter?
Organizers of Global Citizen say that since 2011, the festival has registered more than 19 million “shares” held by its supporters, which pursue many different goals.
It is mentioned that thanks to these actions, world leaders have promised to allocate funds worth more than $ 37 billion, which should affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group announced 390 commitments and announcements that were made as a result of its actions, at least $10 billion of which had already been paid or collected.
The group estimates that the funds provided direct assistance to nearly 649 million people around the world.
One of the most significant commitments is called The Power of Nutrition: a UK partnership of investors and implementation professionals committed to “helping children reach their full potential” has pledged $35 million to help Rwanda end malnutrition in the county. This was done after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens members.
“With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens like you, we can make social injustices about malnutrition a thing of the past,” said Tracy Ullman, Power of Nutrition’s ambassador, during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after more than 5,000 actions were taken calling for Britain to improve nutrition for mothers and children, the government announced funding for the Power of Nutrition project, which will reach 5 million women and children through activities designed to improve nutrition.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on the festival's website, "Why do you think we can end extreme poverty?"
Organizers of Global Citizen say: “It will be a long and difficult journey, where we will stumble and fall from time to time.
But as in the great civil rights and anti-apartheid movements, we will succeed because together we are stronger.
