Beijing has struck back each time, recently imposing tariffs on $60 billion worth of U.S. goods ranging from five to 10 percent.
China has promised that retaliatory measures against the United States will be equivalent every time, and the world's second-largest economy is unlikely to begin to experience at least the slightest difficulties in the near future.
To force Washington to back down is to yield to demands, but to publicly cede to the United States would be too shameful for Xi Jinping, the president of China.
Still, experts say if Beijing can play its cards right, U.S. trade war pressure could provide long-term support to China, reducing the two economies’ interdependence.
“The fact that an early political decision in Washington or Beijing could create conditions that lead to an economic tailspin in any of these countries is in fact much more dangerous than observers have previously acknowledged,” said Abigail Grace, a research fellow at the Center for New American Security, a think tank specializing in Asia.
